Subject: Re: [T2] Moisture in my oil?

On Fri, 15 Mar 2002 abeck(-at-)nt.sympatico.ca wrote:

> How can I have moisture in my oil at -30 to -
> 20 C. In an aircooled engine?

Alan,

Gasoline is composed of (mostly) hydrogen and carbon.  Thus the name
"hydrocarbon".  When you burn gasoline (by adding oxygen), the carbon and
oxygen get together (in a perfect world [1]) to make carbon dioxide (CO2)
and the hydrogen and oxygewn get together to make water (H2O)  No matter
how tight your engine, some of this leaks past the rings and valve guides.
That is why you need crankase ventilation, to relieve the excess pressure
in the case.

If your engine is below 100C, then the water in any blow-by is going to
condense into the oil.  As the water/oil mix gets beaten up by the crank,
it turns into the "mayonaisse" we all know and loath. Once the temp gets
over 100C, that water goes away in pretty short order.

The causes of mayo are:

A type4 engine            (more HP means it does less work/generates
                           less heat)
with high milage          (and lots of blow-by)
run for many short trips  (never gets a chance to warm up)
or without a thermostat   (*never* warms up!)
in a cool/cold climate.   (*reallY* *never* warms up!!!)

Even two or three of these factors will get you some mayo, combine them
and you will see a lot of it!

                           Steve Dolan

